\\\",\\n./tests/test_experiment_comparison_analysis.py:24:from flywire_wave.experiment_analysis_contract import (\\n./tests/test_experiment_comparison_analysis.py:41:from flywire_wave.simulator_result_contract import (\\n./tests/test_experiment_comparison_analysis.py:51:from flywire_wave.stimulus_contract import (\\n./tests/test_experiment_comparison_analysis.py:551:                    contract_version=str(stimulus_metadata[\\\"contract_version\\\"]),\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-005_rationale.md:6:boundary established by `showcase_session.v1` and `dashboard_session.v1`.\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-005_rationale.md:37:- `tests/test_showcase_session_planning.py` now asserts deterministic early-beat\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-005_rationale.md:60:variants, not direct DOM mutations. That keeps the contract at the right\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-005_rationale.md:73:  transition kinds, promote those identifiers into the showcase contract rather\\n./tests/test_validation_circuit.py:24:from flywire_wave.coupling_contract import (\\n./tests/test_validation_circuit.py:39:from flywire_wave.simulator_result_contract import (\\n./tests/test_validation_circuit.py:50:from flywire_wave.stimulus_contract import (\\n./tests/test_validation_circuit.py:715:                contract_version=str(stimulus_metadata[\\\"contract_version\\\"]),\\n./tests/test_validation_circuit.py:1118:                    contract_version=str(stimulus_metadata[\\\"contract_version\\\"]),\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:10:## FW-M10-001 - Freeze a versioned surface-wave model contract, parameter schema, and stability design note\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:14:- Area: wave model / contracts / docs\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:17:Milestone 9 gives the repo a baseline simulator runtime and result-bundle contract, while Milestones 6 and 7 provide operator and coupling assets, but the repo still has no first-class contract for the wave model itself. There is no canonical definition for the chosen model family, state variable names and units, parameter presets, solver-mode identifiers, synaptic source semantics, recovery-state semantics, optional anisotropy or branching modifiers, or which stability assumptions later tickets are allowed to rely on. Without a versioned wave-model contract and a decisive design note, the actual equations will drift into solver internals, manifest parsing will become inconsistent, and later validation work will struggle to distinguish scientific intent from implementation accident.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:20:Define a first-class surface-wave model contract in library code and document the numerical and scientific choices behind it. Centralize wave-model naming, parameter normalization and serialization, contract-version metadata, and design-note discovery so later planning, execution, and result tooling can resolve one canonical `surface_wave` family without hardcoded strings. The design note should compare the candidate model families named in the roadmap, choose the default family for Milestone 10, define the state variables, propagation term, damping term, recovery or refractory behavior, synaptic source injection semantics, nonlinearities, optional anisotropy and branching extensions, and state what counts as physically meaningful behavior versus a numerical artifact.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:24:- The chosen contract records an explicit wave-model contract version plus the normalized parameters and defaults needed to reproduce a `surface_wave` run deterministically, including state-variable definitions, solver family, damping and recovery settings, nonlinearity mode, anisotropy mode, and branching mode.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:26:- `docs/pipeline_notes.md` is updated so the wave-model contract sits alongside the geometry, operator, coupling, stimulus, retinal, and simulator contracts already in the repo.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:27:- Regression coverage verifies deterministic contract serialization, stable model discovery, and compatibility of normalized fixture parameter bundles.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:31:- A focused unit test that builds fixture wave-model metadata and asserts deterministic contract serialization plus discovery\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:60:Assume `FW-M10-001` and the Milestone 9 planning layer are already in place. Favor one planning surface that extends the existing simulator contract rather than a parallel wave-only loader that would drift immediately. Before finishing this ticket, stage all changes made for it and create a non-amended commit that includes those changes.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:72:Implement the first working single-neuron wave-solver core in library code. Build explicit state containers for the chosen field and auxiliary state variables, add sparse operator application against the Milestone 6 assets, and implement the chosen stability-aware integration method with deterministic stepping order and inspectable runtime metadata. The implementation should support localized pulse initialization, propagation and damping on real operator bundles or fixture stand-ins, boundary handling chosen by the contract, and lightweight per-step diagnostics that later validation work can reuse.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:154:- The written bundle follows the shared simulator result contract while adding the wave-specific metadata, state summaries, or snapshot references needed to interpret morphology-resolved runs.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:164:Assume `FW-M10-001` through `FW-M10-005`, the Milestone 9 simulator contract, and the relevant upstream local input contracts are already in place. Favor one clean public execution path over multiple partially overlapping scripts; later mixed-fidelity and analysis work should extend this workflow rather than compete with it. Before finishing this ticket, stage all changes made for it and create a non-amended commit that includes those changes.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:176:Add a parameter-sweep and wave-inspection workflow that consumes normalized `surface_wave` plans and emits deterministic reports. The workflow should support grid or preset-based parameter exploration, repeatable seed handling, compact diagnostics for stability and artifact detection, representative state snapshots or traces, and summary metrics such as wavefront speed, damping behavior, coherence, energy-like quantities, or other contract-approved diagnostics that make the solver's behavior reviewable. Output paths should be deterministic and lightweight enough for local audit and regression testing.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:199:Even if the individual Milestone 10 build tickets land, the repo still needs one explicit integration pass that proves the wave engine is a coherent simulator mode rather than a collection of disconnected solver components. Without a dedicated readiness ticket, it is too easy to stop at isolated solver success while leaving behind manifest drift, hidden contract mismatches, weak stability checks, broken result-bundle compatibility, or undocumented gaps between the single-neuron kernel, coupled execution, visual-input integration, and sweep tooling.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:206:- The verification pass checks contract compatibility across wave-model discovery, manifest planning, single-neuron solver behavior, recovery and nonlinearity modes, anisotropy and branching options, coupling execution, canonical input integration, result serialization, and parameter-sweep or inspection tooling.\\n./docs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:5:Milestone 9 needs one simulator-owned result contract before baseline, wave,\\n./docs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:6:metrics, and UI work diverge. The versioned software contract for that bundle is\\n./docs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:8:`flywire_wave.simulator_result_contract`.\\n./docs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:27:contract path builder, not from ad hoc globbing.\\n./docs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:46:  delay buffers derived from the same coupling contract.\\n./docs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:104:The v1 payload contracts are:\\n./docs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:116:column fields without a contract version bump.\\n./docs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:124:- explicit simulator contract version and design-note version\\n./docs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:163:  back through the shared result-contract helpers and offline viewer, and\\n./docs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:175:columns, or a different meaning for `P0`/`P1`, that is a new contract version,\\n./tests/test_stimulus_registry.py:119:        self.assertEqual(cfg[\\\"stimulus_contract\\\"][\\\"version\\\"], \\\"stimulus_bundle.v1\\\")\\n./tests/test_stimulus_registry.py:120:        self.assertEqual(cfg[\\\"stimulus_bundle_reference\\\"][\\\"contract_version\\\"], \\\"stimulus_bundle.v1\\\")\\n./tests/test_stimulus_registry.py:145:        self.assertEqual(summary[\\\"stimulus_bundle_reference\\\"][\\\"contract_version\\\"], \\\"stimulus_bundle.v1\\\")\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:5:Milestone 15 needs one suite-owned software contract before batch runners,\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:7:meanings for the same experiment family. The versioned contract is\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:9:`flywire_wave.experiment_suite_contract`.\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:11:This note does not replace earlier milestone contracts. It composes with them:\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:18:- `dashboard_session.v1` still owns packaged dashboard-session semantics\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:25:The suite contract freezes two identity concepts:\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:77:The contract owns the family IDs and lineage semantics. It does not decide\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:81:The contract also reserves a separate perturbation-seed hook for ablation\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:131:The suite contract freezes one artifact-role catalog for both upstream inputs\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:145:- `dashboard_session`\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:166:  contract-owned paths\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:220:that is a new contract version rather than a silent edit to\\n./docs/experiment_orchestration_design.md:269:it is the designed mechanism for surfacing remaining contract gaps before\\n./tests/test_milestone12_readiness.py:18:from flywire_wave.readout_analysis_contract import (\\n./tests/test_baseline_families.py:22:from flywire_wave.simulator_result_contract import (\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_aggregation.py:18:from flywire_wave.experiment_suite_contract import WORK_ITEM_STATUS_SUCCEEDED\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-004_rationale.md:7:`scripts/35_showcase_session.py` entrypoint instead of creating a second\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-004_rationale.md:14:contracts:\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-004_rationale.md:16:- `showcase_session.v1` still owns narrative step order, preset identities,\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-004_rationale.md:18:- `dashboard_session.v1` still owns replay semantics and the synchronized\\n./docs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:23:- Motif checks stay tied to the Milestone 7 coupling contract.\\n./docs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:40:  `simulator_result_contract`, and mixed-fidelity findings are lifted directly\\n./tests/test_surface_wave_contract.py:13:from flywire_wave.surface_wave_contract import (\\n./tests/test_surface_wave_contract.py:21:    build_surface_wave_contract_manifest_metadata,\\n./tests/test_surface_wave_contract.py:137:            contract_manifest_metadata = build_surface_wave_contract_manifest_metadata(\\n./tests/test_surface_wave_contract.py:143:                metadata_a[\\\"contract_version\\\"],\\n./tests/test_surface_wave_contract.py:181:            self.assertEqual(contract_manifest_metadata[\\\"version\\\"], SURFACE_WAVE_MODEL_CONTRACT_VERSION)\\n./tests/test_surface_wave_contract.py:183:                contract_manifest_metadata[\\\"parameter_schema_version\\\"],\\n./tests/test_surface_wave_contract.py:187:                contract_manifest_metadata[\\\"selected_roadmap_model_family\\\"],\\n./tests/test_surface_wave_contract.py:191:                contract_manifest_metadata[\\\"default_model_family\\\"],\\n./tests/test_surface_wave_contract.py:206:            self.assertEqual(reference[\\\"contract_version\\\"], SURFACE_WAVE_MODEL_CONTRACT_VERSION)\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-006_rationale.md:9:`showcase_session_planning` and `showcase_player` layers:\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-006_rationale.md:22:than inventing a new review contract. The player resolves those step evidence\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-006_rationale.md:35:- `tests/test_showcase_session_planning.py` now checks deterministic packaged\\n./docs/showcase_mode_notes/FW-M16-006_rationale.md:66:  the showcase contract if they become cross-layer dependencies.\\n./tests/test_baseline_execution.py:24:from flywire_wave.geometry_contract import build_geometry_bundle_paths\\n./tests/test_baseline_execution.py:27:from flywire_wave.retinal_contract import (\\n./tests/test_baseline_execution.py:34:from flywire_wave.simulator_result_contract import (\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:10:## FW-M12-001 - Freeze a versioned readout-analysis contract, task taxonomy, and Milestone 12 design note\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:14:- Area: contracts / docs / analysis architecture\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:17:Milestones 9 through 11 already give the repo deterministic simulator result bundles, shared readout catalogs, `surface_wave` extension artifacts, and mixed-fidelity execution, but there is still no first-class contract for the analysis layer that sits on top of those outputs. The roadmap names direction selectivity, ON/OFF selectivity, optic-flow estimate, motion-vector estimate, latency, synchrony or coherence, phase-gradient statistics, wavefront speed or curvature, and patch activation entropy, yet none of those higher-level quantities currently have one canonical software identity, dependency surface, unit convention, scope rule, or discovery path. Without a versioned readout-analysis contract and decisive design note, later metric code will drift across execution helpers, inspection scripts, readiness reports, and UI payloads, and the team will lose the fairness guarantee that the same declared readout means the same observable across baseline and wave runs.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:20:Define a library-owned Milestone 12 readout-analysis contract and publish a concise design note that locks the metric taxonomy. The contract should distinguish among shared comparison readouts, derived task readouts, wave-only diagnostics, and experiment-level comparison outputs; define stable metric IDs, units, scopes, required source artifacts, and canonical discovery helpers; and state which quantities are allowed to depend only on shared readouts versus which may consume wave-only patch or phase artifacts. The design note should stay tightly aligned with the locked Milestone 1 hypothesis, the T4a/T5a terminal readout boundary, and the existing `simulator_result_bundle.v1` invariants, while also naming the first task families, null-test hooks, and UI-facing outputs Milestone 12 must support.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:23:- There is one canonical readout-analysis contract in library code with explicit identifiers and normalization helpers for shared readout metrics, derived task metrics, wave-only diagnostics, and experiment-level comparison outputs.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:24:- The contract records stable metric IDs, units, scope rules, required source artifact classes, and fairness notes that explain whether a quantity must be computable from the shared readout catalog or may consume wave-only extension artifacts.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:26:- `docs/pipeline_notes.md` is updated so the Milestone 12 analysis contract sits alongside the existing geometry, coupling, retinal, simulator, and `surface_wave` contracts.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:27:- Regression coverage verifies deterministic contract serialization, stable metric discovery, and normalization of representative fixture metric definitions.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:31:- A focused unit test that builds fixture analysis-contract metadata and asserts deterministic serialization plus discovery of metric and output definitions\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:78:- The analysis output is compatible with the Milestone 12 contract and can be serialized into comparison-ready metric rows or structured summaries without special-case UI logic.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:98:Build the first library-owned task-decoder interface for Milestone 12 and ship deterministic motion-vector and optic-flow estimators through that interface. The implementation should consume only declared shared readouts plus the normalized task-analysis plan and any allowed local context such as stimulus direction labels or retinotopic geometry metadata, and it should emit explicit task outputs with stable units, conventions, and diagnostic metadata. Support the current local motion-patch vertical slice first, but keep the interface extensible enough that later larger-field optic-flow tasks can reuse it without changing the contract.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:104:- The resulting task outputs are compatible with the Milestone 12 analysis contract and discoverable through shared helpers rather than hidden inside one report generator.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:112:Assume `FW-M12-001` through `FW-M12-003`, the Milestone 8 stimulus and retinal contracts, and the locked Milestone 1 fairness rules are already in place. The key guardrail is that task decoders may be richer than raw readouts without becoming wave-only cheats. Do not attempt to create a git commit as part of this ticket.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:121:The roadmap also calls for wave-specific structure metrics such as synchrony or coherence, phase-gradient statistics, wavefront speed or curvature, and patch activation entropy, but the repo currently exposes those ideas only partially through Milestone 10 inspection helpers. There is still no reusable, contract-backed analysis layer that turns wave patch traces, state summaries, or `surface_wave` extension artifacts into deterministic diagnostics with declared semantics. Without that layer, the same wave run could be described differently by inspection tooling, readiness reports, and later UI code, and mixed-fidelity follow-on work would have no stable interface for reporting wave structure.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:124:Implement the reusable Milestone 12 wave-diagnostic kernels that consume wave-capable result bundles and emit deterministic morphology-aware metrics. Reuse the existing Milestone 10 inspection logic where it already provides a good starting point, but refactor the relevant computations into contract-backed analysis functions that can be called by offline reports, experiment-level comparison workflows, and later UI data preparation. Keep these diagnostics explicitly separate from the shared comparison readout catalog so fairness remains visible: they are allowed wave-only diagnostics, not hidden replacements for the shared readout surface.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:129:- The resulting outputs are discoverable through the Milestone 12 contract as wave-only diagnostics and do not mutate the meaning of shared readout IDs or shared comparison metrics.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:164:Assume `FW-M12-001` through `FW-M12-005`, the Milestone 9 result-bundle contract, and the Milestone 10 execution workflow are already in place. This ticket is the core of the task layer: traces become experiment-level evidence here. Do not attempt to create a git commit as part of this ticket.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:199:Even if the earlier Milestone 12 tickets land individually, the repo still needs one explicit integration pass showing that readout analysis, task decoding, wave diagnostics, comparison orchestration, export packaging, and UI-facing payloads actually work together as one coherent layer. Without a dedicated readiness ticket, it will be too easy to stop at isolated metric kernels or one successful report while leaving behind hidden contract mismatches, fairness regressions, broken discovery paths, or analysis outputs that only work for a single hand-crafted fixture.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:202:Perform a senior-level verification pass over the completed Milestone 12 implementation and publish a concise readiness report in-repo. The pass should exercise the full local workflow on fixture assets and at least one representative experiment manifest, verify that the declared analysis contract matches shipped behavior, confirm that baseline-versus-wave comparisons are quantitative rather than purely visual, and record any remaining scientific or engineering risks that Milestones 13 and 14 must respect. Fix defects or documentation drift directly where reasonable, and turn the rest into explicit follow-on issues rather than leaving them implicit.\\n./agent_tickets/milestone_12_readouts_task_layer_tickets.md:206:- The verification pass checks contract compatibility across analysis-plan resolution, shared-readout kernels, task decoders, wave-diagnostic kernels, experiment-level comparison orchestration, packaged exports, and UI-facing payload discovery.\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:13:from flywire_wave.dashboard_session_contract import DASHBOARD_SESSION_CONTRACT_VERSION\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:14:from flywire_wave.experiment_analysis_contract import (\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:17:from flywire_wave.experiment_suite_contract import (\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:62:    build_experiment_suite_contract_metadata,\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:74:    load_experiment_suite_contract_metadata,\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:76:    write_experiment_suite_contract_metadata,\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:80:from flywire_wave.simulator_result_contract import (\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:83:from flywire_wave.validation_contract import VALIDATION_LADDER_CONTRACT_VERSION\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:90:def _mutate_contract_fixture(\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:248:    def test_default_contract_exposes_milestone15_taxonomy(self) -> None:\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:249:        metadata = build_experiment_suite_contract_metadata()\\n./tests/test_experiment_suite_contract.py:251:        self.assertEqual(metadata[\\\"contract_version\\\"], EXPERIMENT_SUITE_CONTRACT_VERSION